You see now the difference between no-trump and suit play;|PG||AT| at no-trump East's Queen must win.|PG||AT| But here spades are trumps. Since you have no more clubs, you can play a small spade (the four-spot),|PG||AT| thereby winning the trick by ruffling.|cp|8|at|^*B*^*N|cp||at||PG||NT|
^B@2|cp|8|at|^*I* "Ruffing" |cp||at|and|cp|8|at| "trumping" |cp||at|are synonymous terms. "Ruff" was the name of an old game of cards preceding, and closely resembling Whist. The name came to be applied to the act of trumping because this mode of winning a trick was the outstanding characteristic of the play. At Whist all hands were played with some suit as trump; the no-trump contract came into use with Bridge. 
