QX|12B03,WHEN NOT TO LEAD TRUMPS IMMEDIATELY|
HT|e|cs|1|cp|4|fp||
at|
^-{    WHEN NOT TO LEAD TRUMPS IMMEDIATELY    }
^-|cp||fp||at|^B@2^Y@3
A very common occurrence which necessitates postponement of the trump lead is a finessing situation which must be taken advantage of while entries are still available. The following deal drives home this point.|PG||NT||
sk|s|pn|You,,,|st||md|3SAQT84H973D86CA84,S65HJ85DAKT5CJ973,SJ73HAQT4D942CK62,SK92HK62DQJ73CQT5|sv|0|rh||ah|Deal 2|NT|^B@2
You are the Declarer playing a contract of four spades.|mb|p|mb|p|mb|4S|an|To speed up the play|mb|p|mb|p|mb|p|pg||
pc|dK|at| West's opening lead is the King of diamonds,|PG||pc|d2|pc|d7|pc|d6|pg||
pc|dA|at| followed by the Ace,|PG||pc|d4|pc|d3|pc|d8|pg||
pc|d5|AT| and, on the third round, the five of diamonds.|PG||pc|d9|pc|dJ|at|
When this third diamond trick comes up to your hand, you have no more of the suit led and therefore trump with the four of spades.|PG||pc|s4|pg||NT|^B@2
Looking at the hand as a whole, you see that you have a perfect finessing position in trumps (spades), but you cannot finesse if you lead trumps immediately, for you are in the wrong hand. You therefore do not lead trumps at the fourth trick, but cast about for some means of entering Dummy's hand. |pg||NT|^B@2
You have two certain entries to the Dummy: the heart Ace and club King. You have two more entries that are possible: the heart Queen and the heart Ten. The heart Queen offers a distinct probability as an entry card, but the Ten cannot be considered with any seriousness, for both the King and Jack must be in West's hand if the Ten is to become an actual entry.|PG||NT|^B@2
Which entry shall you utilize at this point? The heart suit offers a finesse, too—in fact, a double finesse (against King and Jack).|PG||NT|^B@2
However, by taking the heart finesse now, you run a risk of losing the lead and being obliged to postpone leading trumps until still later. The club King looks like the logical entry card to use at this juncture.|PG||NT|^B@2
But (every good player, remember, goes through a mental process similar to this on every hand he plays), giving second thought to the use of the club King, you note that as soon as it is gone you will have left only one controlling card in that suit. Then if the spade finesse loses and the Opponents lead another club pronto, you will be forced to win with your Ace, while still holding a club that is sure to lose.|PG||NT|^B@2
If you put off relinquishing your control of the club suit, however, you may be able, eventually, to discard that losing club on the extra heart in Dummy's hand (you hold seven hearts against the Opponents' six).|PG||NT|^B@2
After considering every angle, then, you decide to take the heart finesse at once. |PG||at| You therefore lead a low heart from your hand and finesse the Ten from Dummy.|PG||pc|h3|pc|h5|pc|hT|pg||at| East wins with the King|pc|hK|PG||AT| and returns a club.|PG||pc|c5|pc|c4|pc|c7|at|
You can win this in either hand, but you decide to let the trick run around to Dummy's King, as you feel that leading trumps has been put off long enough. |PG||pc|cK|pg||NT|^B@2
You must choose which of Dummy's trumps to lead.|pg||lb|*CWhich card would you play from Dummy if you were the Declarer? The quiz is not part of the book.^^sj^sj73|AT| Not a low one, certainly, because, if you win in your own hand with either the Ten or the Queen, you will be obliged to do some squirming to find your way into the Dummy again, You must try to keep the lead in the Dummy in order to facilitate a second trump lead through East, who may not play the King on the first round.|PG||NT|^B@2
Therefore you lead the Jack,|pc|sJ|PG||AT| on which East plays low,|pc|s2|PG||AT| you play low from your hand,|pc|s8|pc|s5|PG||AT| and West also plays low. The Jack holds the trick, keeping the lead in the Dummy, |PG||at| from where you now lead a low trump,|pc|s3|PG||AT| winning with the Ten in your hand.|PG||pc|s9|pc|sT|pc|s6|pg||NT|^B@2 
Your count tells you that the King is now the only trump outstanding, so you drop it by leading your Ace.|pc|sA|PG||pc|c3|pc|s7|pc|sK|pg||sk||at| The rest of this hand is pie. The King of hearts is gone, leaving Dummy's Ace-Queen high. You lead these two rounds of hearts, dropping all the outstanding cards of this suit, throwing off your losing club on Dummy's four of hearts. You thus make the 10 tricks called for by your contract of four spades.|PG||
pc|h7|pc|h8|pc|hQ|pc|h2|pg||
pc|hA|pc|h6|pc|h9|pc|hJ|pg||
pc|h4|pc|cT|pc|c8|pc|c9|sc|y|mc|10|pg||NT|
^B@2This hand contained three sharp points of interest. |PG||NT|
^B@2The first was |CP|8|AT| - the postponement of leading trumps in order to get into the opposite hand to finesse the suit.|PG||CP||aT|
The second was |CP|8|AT| - the preference given to the heart suit for purposes of entry into the Dummy, so as not to relinquish control of a side suit (clubs).|PG||CP||AT|
The third was |CP|8|AT| - the unblocking play in trumps (by finessing the Jack from Dummy first) in order to allow as many leads as possible from the proper hand.|PG||CP||AT|
These three points or plays occur time and time again, and you will therefore be repaid for remembering their principles. |PG||NT||bt||sc||
