^-|CS||CP||fp||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3B.|FP||cp||AT| My second note is about counting out the trump suit:|PG||AT|

Many players have trouble remembering if all trumps have been drawn. Here are two tips that can be used to help you:|PG||AT|

1) Rather than counting out how many trumps have been played, just remember how many trumps remain in the opponents' hands. Thus, if you have an 8 card fit, the opponents start out with 5 trumps between their 2 hands. If you draw one round, and both opponents follow, you now only need to remember there are only 3 trumps remaining in the two hands. If you then draw another round, and both opponents follow again, you now only need to remember there is just one outstanding trump remaining.|PG||AT|

2) Don't forget to deduct one trump from the remaining count if the opponents ruff one of your tricks. This is a very common error that I see over and over again, even by very good players. For example, if you have an eight card fit, and the opponents have ruffed a trick, there are now only 4 trumps remaining. Had they not ruffed, it would take at least 3 rounds to draw all the trumps. However, once they ruff, you often can draw the remaining trump in two rounds.|PG||LF|CH-13-P-1.LIN| 

 